 Service Mesh Configuration
Prerequisites
Before starting this lab, you should have:

Basic understanding of Kubernetes concepts (pods, services, deployments)
Familiarity with YAML configuration files
Experience with command-line tools
Knowledge of microservices architecture fundamentals
A Linux machine with at least 4GB RAM and 2 CPU cores
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Install and configure Istio service mesh on Kubernetes
Deploy microservices with Istio sidecar injection
Configure traffic routing rules using VirtualServices
Implement basic traffic management patterns
Environment Setup
Step 1: Install Required Tools
Install kubectl:

curl -LO "https://dl.k8s.io/release/$(curl -L -s https://dl.k8s.io/release/stable.txt)/bin/linux/amd64/kubectl"
chmod +x kubectl
sudo mv kubectl /usr/local/bin/
Install Minikube:

curl -LO https://storage.googleapis.com/minikube/releases/latest/minikube-linux-amd64
sudo install minikube-linux-amd64 /usr/local/bin/minikube
Install Istioctl:

curl -L https://istio.io/downloadIstio | sh -
cd istio-*
export PATH=$PWD/bin:$PATH
cd ..
Step 2: Start Kubernetes Cluster
minikube start --memory=4096 --cpus=2 --driver=docker
Verify cluster is running:

kubectl cluster-info
kubectl get nodes
Task 1: Install and Configure Istio
Step 1: Install Istio
Install Istio with the demo profile:

istioctl install --set profile=demo -y
Verify installation:

kubectl get pods -n istio-system
Wait until all pods show STATUS as "Running".

Step 2: Enable Automatic Sidecar Injection
Create a namespace with Istio injection enabled:

kubectl create namespace microservices
kubectl label namespace microservices istio-injection=enabled
Verify the label:

kubectl get namespace microservices --show-labels
Step 3: Deploy Sample Microservices
