curl -H "user-type: premium" http://$GATEWAY_URL
Expected output: Should consistently return v2 response.

Check Istio Configuration
istioctl analyze -n microservices
Expected output: No validation issues found.

Troubleshooting Tips
Pods not starting:

Check if Minikube has enough resources: minikube status
View pod logs: kubectl logs <pod-name> -n microservices -c istio-proxy
Sidecar not injected:

Verify namespace label: kubectl get namespace microservices --show-labels
Recreate pods: kubectl rollout restart deployment -n microservices
Traffic routing not working:

Check VirtualService status: kubectl get virtualservice -n microservices
Validate configuration: istioctl analyze -n microservices
Check gateway: kubectl get gateway -n microservices
Cannot access gateway:

Verify ingress gateway is running: kubectl get pods -n istio-system | grep ingress
Check service type: kubectl get svc -n istio-system istio-ingressgateway
Conclusion
You have successfully:

Installed Istio service mesh on a Kubernetes cluster
Deployed microservices with automatic sidecar injection
Configured traffic routing using VirtualServices and DestinationRules
Implemented traffic splitting and header-based routing patterns
Service meshes like Istio provide powerful traffic management capabilities without requiring changes to application code. These skills are essential for managing complex microservices architectures in production environments, enabling advanced deployment strategies like canary releases, A/B testing, and gradual rollouts.

